# Commit and PR conventions

Always follow these rules when drafting commit messages, commit plans, PR titles, or PR descriptions.

## Commits

- **Conventional Commits:** `type(scope): imperative subject` — ≤ ~72 chars, no trailing period
- **One logical change per commit** — do not mix unrelated feature, refactor, and fix
- **Commit plan first** when multiple logical changes exist on a branch (ordered list with type, subject, files)
- **Only run `git commit` when the user explicitly asks**
- Do not amend, squash, or use `--no-verify` unless the user explicitly requests

## Pull requests

- **Title:** Same format as commit subject (Conventional Commits)
- **Body sections (required):** Overview, Changes, Potential risks, Testing, Related
- Imperative mood; runnable Testing steps when applicable

## PR merge commit (GitHub merge commit)

When drafting **PR merge info** or merge **extended description**: keep default `Merge pull request #…` subject; body uses Summary, `Changes:`, `Commits merged:`, `Post-merge:` — see **`CANONICAL_DOCS_PATH/pull-requests.md`**.

## Full specs and examples

- Commits: **`CANONICAL_DOCS_PATH/commits-logical-order.md`**
- PRs: **`CANONICAL_DOCS_PATH/pull-requests.md`**
